I have been watching for just the right deal on a slip-on exhaust for my bike since 2006. Seriously. That's how determined I was to get my money's worth. So when I saw this offering from DG at Amazon for $159 shipped I jumped all over it. That is DIRT CHEAP for a slip-on, and it looks like a quality piece. DG has been around a while too, catering mostly to ATV's, and while the brand isn't considered to be the best, it certainly is respectable. I believe if their attempt to break into the motorcycle market takes hold this price will go up.I'm no expert in metallurgy, but I'm guessing the pipe is stainless steel, the outer muffler is polished aluminum, and the front and back end caps are cast aluminum - all of which are corrosion resistant and should look nice for many years. Even the hex screws that attach the end caps (and allow access to the NFS approved spark arrestor and muffler packing) appear to be stainless steel. (UPDATE - Nope. A magnet test on the screws has since confirmed them to be just steel... very shiny steel. Chrome plated maybe?) There are no painted surfaces to scratch, fade, or chip. There was no ugly, weak, strap-type bracket to install. All mounting points were welded on. It fit perfectly, came with everything I needed, took me about 30 minutes to install from start to finish, and it looks great on the bike.To get the most performance you should re-jet. My bike was already jetted bigger in anticipation of a pipe and was a bit rich, so the DG exhaust instantly made it run better. There was a marked power increase down low in the RPM range. It revs quicker from just above idle to low mid-range. This is right where I need it 90% of the time, but after that you're just making more noise.There are a few things that prevent a 5 star review - 1) This thing is LOUD - as in OBNOXIOUS. It sounds almost like a piece of straight pipe. I was behind a super loud Harley at a red light once and he revved his engine to be cool, and a little old lady on the sidewalk screamed and dropped her groceries. The paper bag split and fresh vegetables etc went rolling in all directions. I don't get off on terrorizing grandmothers and impugning cops. Thankfully there are 4 or 5 different diameter quiet inserts available for about $25 a piece, each supplying a different noise level. The 1     insert is the quietest (94 decibels claimed) and makes the least power, but it is still supposed to be more powerful than with the stock exhaust. Though it does lessen the value factor, I will be ordering that one and plan to use it most of the time. 2) I wish the exhaust plume were directed more down and towards the side. Unlike with the stock muffler, the hot, unimpeded exhaust gasses now liberally bathe the right side of the plastic fender. If any discoloration begins to occur I'm thinking I might even fabricate and install a curved tail piece to direct things away from the back of the bike. We shall see if all that becomes necessary. (UPDATE - This was completely resolved by remounting the pipe with the bracket on top of the blinker bracket instead of under it. That and a slight     tweaking     of the mounting brackets. Wish I had thought to try this before I melted a tail light.) And 3) It seems to me to be on the heavy side for an aftermarket pipe.Anyway, all in all the good far outweighs the bad. I am pleased with my purchase. If your goal is to gain a little power, make some serious noise, look good doing it, and get better than average value for your money, the DG O Series Slip-on Exhaust might just be the pipe for you!

I do field service motor repair and needed something to give me an RPM.  This works, to a point.If you're familiar with real strobe lights, you know they  #34;freeze #34; the shaft view: e.g., a white line drawn on the pulley looks like a white line when synced. The Pyle doesn't, but rather the white line looks like a whitish arc of about 30. As you change the LEDs' flash speed, a particular artifact on the rotating part -- say, a largish scratch -- will slowly appear to quit rotating.  But it never really comes in focus: you can simply see that the various scratches don't seem to be moving. Or a fan blade appears as a larger fuzzy blade.  Sorry, it's hard to explain.  I suppose it's because the multiple LEDs' turn on / turn off times are not fast enough, or aren't exactly synchronized together (at typical motor speeds).  But even given that limitation, you can tell what the speed is, which is what you want to know.Its operation is fairly easy.  The Power button turns it on, but does not activate the flash, which is invoked from a button on the right side. It powers up in the Gross Adjust mode.  Use that to get within a range, then press the Fine button to creep into the sweet spot ( #34;Fine #34; is displayed on the LCD screen).  The LEDs are bright enough to work from a reasonable distance, say three feet. The display maintains its last mark when you stop the LEDs, which is helpful.  I haven't verified battery life, nor its toughness, though I've been carrying it in my toolbag for awhile and it still works.  I don't use the included carrying case, since it's so big.The thing you need to be careful about is that you will see the sync image at multiples of the rotating speed, so you must start from the bottom and work your way up.  That's not too tedious, since the Gross adjust goes quickly, and you can usually tell when it's approaching sync.Be seriously aware that a slow LED flash can cause problems with people prone to seizures, so do be careful about that.In short, for a fast, cheap way of determining RPMs, the Pyle does what it claims.  It's just not a real Strobe.

I received this antenna as a gift, so I didn't personally purchase this through Amazon.Installation is really easy after you do all the necessary cleaning and prep (alcohol wipe down to remove the wax).1. Just unscrew the original antenna off the mount.2. Tape the alignment guide on your car.3. Attach the helix wire with the provided screw.4. Remove the cover of the 3M double sided tape and place the shark fin (Beat-Sonic calls it a Dolphin antenna) cover down over the factory antenna base and between the cutout in the alignment guide and press down to make the cover stick on your roof.Simple as that.  It took me about 10 minutes.It's painted to match the original color of your car so the installation looks factory and cool.  But.......you do lose some antenna gain.  I tuned onto popular local AM stations (for those of you in the Los Angeles area, the stations I used were KNX 1070 and 790 KABC) during installation.  When I made the connection as described in step 3 above, the radio reception was just as good as the factory antenna.  This was a dry test fit, so I didn't remove the cover of the double sided tape.  As I was lowering the fin cover over the factory base (step 4) I started to lose the signal (more static).  I removed my hand just to make sure my body wasn't blocking any of the signal, but no improvement.  I lifted the fin cover off and the signal came back.  Bottom line, the shark fin cover is not totally RF transparent and you are going to lose signal.If you live in a major city, this may not be an issue.  If you're far from the city and constantly struggling to get an AM signal, then I would not recommend this antenna.If I were to rate this on a scale from 1 to 10: Installation - 10; cool factor - 10; Performance - 7

I got this to use to hook up extra items in my truck.  The selling point was the USB port.  I have 3 items that charge via usb, and thought hey, one size fits all right. I put some screws in to it and mounted it inside my glove compartment.  The LED is nice because it is red (blue is just silly)  Red is great because it matches the dash lights and does not glare at night and ruin night vision while driving.Here is the only down side.  I plugged in my cell phone (a Tmobile Google My Touch) via a usb to mini usb cable.  It starts to charge but gets nowhere.  My phone dies jsut a little bit slower and if you are talking to texting it seems to not help at all.  I plugged in my GPS and same results.  I tried a few items, and asked the Apple Store about the problem.  They say they have the same issue with ipods/iphones/ipads.  It is so simple no one caught it.You assume power is power.  The apple issue is how many MW not Volts and it translates to here as well.  This jack puts out less than 500mw.  The iPad requires almost 5000mw, Ipods are in the 1000mw range, and my cell phone requires 1200mw.  What this means is you wont damage your device, however with such little power, it is unlikely going to charge.  It will show a charge indicator but remember my phone, needing more than double the power to properly charge.  Now i am sure if left for a long period, or if you were just trying to maintain a phone a little longer it may help.  However for it's intended purpose is does not work.  It is sad but the rest of the unit works great, I just use the car charger still and no usb.

I was having trouble with (2005 Yukon XL 1500 4x4) when I turned on my blinker it would turn on the hazard lights.  It started at first with the only the right and then switched to the left blinker.  This is a pretty easy fix.  It is located on the back side of the fuse block underneath the steering wheel.  You have to remove the trim around the speedometer and then remove the plastic panel under the steering wheel.  It will be on the left hand side.  I had to unclip the fuse block to move it forward a bit to get enough wiggle room to remove the old flasher module. It is in pretty snug but with enough wiggling it does come out. The original flasher has a different part number, but I think this is a very common problem and this part works perfect and seems to be the new replacement part.

2/23/11 - Update: Well, we recently used this in very bright sunlight, with the GPS placed on the dashboard. Unfortunately, the sunlight totally washed out the GPS screen, and since the angle of the mount is not adjustable, there wasn't anything I could do to make the screen easier to see. Had to keep the GPS balanced in the cupholder. It would have been great to have a few different angle adjustments to minimize this problem. I've dropped my rating down to 3 stars.___Original review - In California, until recently it was illegal to mount a GPS (or anything else) on the windshield. That meant that you either needed to affix a GPS mount to the dashboard, possibly marring the surface over time, or deal with the slipping and sliding of a loose unit as you drove. I was in the latter camp, and ended up putting the GPS in the cup holder more often than not, occasionally picking it up to make sure I was heading in the right direction.I actually spent quite a bit of time looking for solutions to this problem. Believe it or not, no one seemed to make a non-adhesive GPS mount for the dashboard. I tried a beanbag for a while, but this was obviously not the best solution (people gave me funny looks when they saw a Beanie Baby on my dashboard).This mount by Heininger is exactly what I was looking for. It is a molded soft foam/latex frame which has a grippy bottom to keep everything in place on your dashboard, an angled design to keep the GPS at a good viewing angle, and an open back in case you have cords to attach to the GPS. Most importantly, once you get to your destination you can just throw the mount on the floor so that no one knows you have a GPS unit in your car.The only significant downside is that since there is technically nothing that is keeping your GPS unit in place except gravity, sudden turns or stops/starts can potentially cause the GPS unit to tumble out of the mount. As long as that doesn't fit your driving style, this mount should work well for you. Also, it is somewhat on the large side, which allows a widescreen GPS to fit nicely in it, but it may be too big for some smaller units, such as the TomTom One.

When buying LED fixtures for off road they should have a MINIMUM IP rating of 64,  RIGID INDUSTRIES I think are IP68,  these are very close at IP67:The two numbers in the IP67 rating code rating refer to:6 -      Dust Protected     ; Totally protected against dust ingress.; complete protection against contact7-      Immersion Protected     ; Protected against short periods of immersion in water.Ingress of water in harmful quantity shall not be possible when the enclosure is immersed in water under defined conditions of pressure and time (up to 1 m of submersion). Test duration: 30 minutes;  Immersion at depth of at least 1 m measured at bottom of device, and at least 15 cm measured at top of deviceSo unless your mounting these to your underwater submarine they should do just fine under normal, and by normal I mean severe off road, conditions.  Odds are if these LED's stop working because of water damage you'll probably be getting a new vehicle too.  God help anybody who cuts me off at night now!

Good quality lights. I have owend KCs before and have always been happy. I recently upgraded all my lights to HID.  I stumbled across these and figured I'd give them a shot. Well even though they are made of plastic, they seem very stout and solid. I kind of like the fact that they will not rust like the metal ones do over time. They are alot more solid than other plastic housing lights I've owen from some of the competitors.  These still use the fluted glass design as the lens rather than the free form reflector design which I dont care for. Being HID these are a nicely reasonably priced light compared to other options. They seem to have a decent beam pattern and light up the night very well. I chose the driving lights over the spots simply because I wanted a little spread sacrificing some distance. Well even in driving beam these reach out plenty for my needs. They are alot brighter than halogens and have a built in ballast unlike some. Even the wiring harness is of good quality, alot better than some others I have owened. Plenty of wire provided to reach where needed. The bulb kelvin color in these is just about perfect, a nice warm color. I would say right about 4500k give or take, which is about the perfect balance between true white with a hint of yellow to go easy on the eyes, unlike others that are 5k or 6K which is a tad too much blue and strains the eyes some.  I have the warn 7000s, which is a 7 #34; hid and I think for the money these are a better buy. My warns put out a tad more blue color than I like, prob about 6K.  Although I mounted these KC 6 #34; ers up on the windsheild pillars of my jeep, I wish I had a set of these in the 8 #34;er version down on my bumper instead of the warns really. I think the 8 #34; version would prob perform a tad better and would compliment these 6 #34; KCs very well. I wouldnt say they are top of the line hids by any means, but for the average wheeler that does trails, they are exactly what I was looking for and live up to my expectations completly for the price. Well worth the little extra over the standard halogen models. Of course the excellent KC 23 year warranty helps also. So if you break them or they go out on you, send them back and they will give you new ones or repair them, you cant go wrong. If you are a desert racer and want a super high quality HID, then fork out the dough and buy one of the more expensive higher top of the line models. Again, for what I needed these fit the bill pretty well. Also for those that are considering buying some cheap halogen lights and retrofit them over to hid, well why bother? These are what your looking for. By the time you buy a cheap hid kit, some cheap lights, hack them up and install the hid bulbs into the housings and then have half arss quality light focus with big ballast boxes mounted externally exposed to the elements and looking ugly, you can have these instead. They are alot cleaner and provide what you were looking for in the first place with a good warranty and less hassle to boot.

Crankshaft Position Sensor install is practically common sense.  On the 2.4L The notch matches position on the crank gear with the tooth having the dimple.  After you install the plate if you can't see the dimple when looking through the notch then you put the plate in flipped backasswards.  Your timing belt would get eaten soon and the plate would soon hit the position sensor pickup if you don't put it in correctly.  To install a new plate in means getting the gear off.  I use a pipe from an old chain link fence gate and slip it over my breaker bar and tap the starter.  That trick has worked each of 3 times on three different vehicles.  The trouble with that is you CANNOT tighten the bolt without taking off the flywheel access and blocking the flywheel.  DO NOT attempt to tighten (or loosen) the center bolt by holding the Harmonic Balancer in some fashion.

I have a work truck that I bought used from a farmer's coop. A bad knock sensor was one of the problems.Unfortunately, the knock sensor is in the middle of GM's Gen IV V8 smallblock. This wouldn't be so bad if the factory had actually sealed the area around the knock sensor. But the Canadian plant did not and allowed any water that ended up under the hood to pool over the knock sensors. The obvious result? It rusts and stops working which throws up the check engine light. And you have to take off the intake manifold to get at it.When you go through that much effort, and don't know if it works until everything is put back into place, you don't want any possible problems. So you want things like having both sensors being uniform and from the same company so the computer doesn't get messed up.But when I ordered two (there are two in every engine), I recieved two knock sensors made from different companies in different boxes. Only one was delphi, the other was an off brand. It ended up working, but it is not the situation I wanted to be in.

Mercedes fixed that problem for free with Campaign # 2009100001 (still available), but forced me to pay for the inspection of the wiring to see if oil leaked through. I'm now requesting a refund from Mercedes HQ for the inspection and this O2 sensor.  I'll write back with any success/failure.

I installed a pair of westin tubes almost 10 years ago.  After they rusted off, I got the aluminum sure step and this installation kit.  Probably the worst instructions I have ever seen.  Seriously, how hard is it to write some decent instructions. I could spend 10 minutes and write a better set of instructions.  After you get one side done, you figure it out.  The worst offense is that the brackets aren't engineered to fit correctly.  The bracket will bend the lower lip of the sheet metal as you tighten down the bolts.  It should have been at 90 degrees, but it is at about 80 degrees so the thin metal is stressed.  The bolts are barely big enough to get threaded, because of the incorrectly engineered bracket.  Once you finally get it threaded, it starts to bend the metal out.  Like the other poster mentioned, the self tapping screws are barely long enough and you have to be very delicate while drilling and set the clutch on the drill low so you don't drill out the hole completely like I did on my first hole.  I'm not convinced it will hold.  I may tack weld the brackets on if it gets loose.  I'm not thrilled about drilling holes in my truck.  There are plenty of factory holes and options that should have been utilized.  I wish I had gone with a different option/brand.  With stressed metal and questionable self tapped screws, not sure how long this will last.  I'm pretty sure I will need to weld these on at some point, if I don't just rip them off and start with a different brand.  This is on a 2001 F150 supercrew.

I replaced the bolts with 3/8 X 16 X 3/4 #9 bolts from lowes with lock washers. I had to compress the spring and loosen the nut but it had just enough clearance. So my 1/2 hr job turned into an all day affair, considering that the local auto store wanted $440 in labor I still consider a positive day was had, good thing I had access to another car though to get extra parts.Who ever is supplying the little bolts on the top plate should be replaced by teneco or monroe, I've been turning wrenchs for 40 yrs and also used to work in a tool and die shop that made dies for header bolts so I know a defective bolt when I get one! Still I love the new ride but if your doing this yourself, make sure you have a spring compressor just in case and whatever you do     BE CAREFULL WITH THE TOP BOLTS     !Lastly this has nothing to do with amazon, I could of put the car back together and sent the defective unit back and who knows what would of been said back and forth as to the bolts quality? I bought these shocks for my 2006 Chevrolet Express 3500 Van. I was troubled after comparing the new shock to the OEM shock. They are not exactly alike. The original shock has a large rubber isolator with a steel sleeve, and a long upper post. The Monroe shock looks the same on the lower mount, but the upper isolator is MUCH smaller than the original, and looks like it belongs on a half-ton truck. I contacted Monroe   they assured me that the replacement shock will work work fine in this application. I've been driving with the new shocks for a week and they have helped soften the ride somewhat. Just be sure to re-tighten the upper mounting nut AFTER the truck is sitting on the front wheels. I purchased these Monroe quick-struts 2 1/2 years ago to replace a broken coil spring on my wife's 02 Focus (a common problem for that vintage Focus, thanks Ford). They were ideal for my situation because I got the whole spring/strut assembly for about what I would have paid for just springs. As a bonus, I didn't have to mess around with compressing the springs, as it was just a matter of bolting the new assembly into place. They were an exact replacement fit and they ride the same as the stock spring/struts (note: the car seemed to ride 'higher' for a few months, but the springs have since settled in). I would have reviewed them earlier but after installing them, I began hearing faint suspension related noises and held off until I tracked down the source. That turned out to be a failing motor mount (again, thanks Ford). Long story short, I completely forgot to review these struts. So with the hindsight of 2 1/2 years and 28,000 miles, I can report they are still working beautifully. No leaks at the struts, springs are in good shape, and an overall stock like handling suspension.

The Raybestos sway bar links for our 2002 Dodge Grand Caravan were a great replacement for the worn out OEM units.  Installation on the new struts was very simple. I had to use a sawzall to cut the ball joints off, but since I was replacing the strut, I only cut the bottom from the sway bar.  I left the top attached to the strut so that I could remove the strut and link as one piece from the car.If you are keeping the struts, use a penetrating oil (PBlaster or equivalent) for several days prior to attempting to remove the old links.

Far superior to the OEM Toyota parts, which is not always the case with replacements. The link looks heavier, comes with larger hardware and it has a grease zerk (also not on the OEM part). Don't let the crummy photo fool you, this is a top notch product.

Used to replace the VERY worn and old endlinks on a 1999 Subaru Forester. Made the car slightly more responsive as far as body roll and turn-in. Have these paired with a 22mm Whiteline swaybar. All required parts for the install, even grease, are included.Other than thinking these are kind of pricey, I also think you get what you pay for. Whiteline is an excellent company who produces excellent products and it's worth paying the premium. I've had the pleasure of dealing with their support when a product I ordered didn't work for the application they said it would in their catalog. I received immediate support and a replacement product free of charge.

Recently my Toyota 1996 Camry LE showed the symptom of needing to turn the key several times for it to start. I bought the starter kit and a Stanley 201-piece tool set to fix this problem. From beginning to finish, the task took me 2.5 hours (1.5 hours on taking the starter motor/solenoid out; 15 minutes on replacing the parts using the kit and cleaning the solenoid, and 45 minutes putting everything back together). Replacing the parts using the kit is really easy; what's difficult for me are loosening the two 14mm screws fixing the starter motor/solenoid and the engine (i.e., super tight and in confined space).

I used this product to replace my failing solenoid contacts on my 1999 Toyota Corolla.  Toyota will not sell these items individually to you, so the alternative was to buy a new starter from Toyota or a refurbished starter from Toyota both being in the $300 - $200 range respectively.  Another alternative was going to the auto parts store and purchasing a cheap Mexican made starter motor for my Toyota.  The problem with the aftermarket unit is that the quality does not come close or compare to the quality of the Japan made Denso unit that comes with the Corolla.  After researching the starting issues I had with my vehicle and using a simple voltmeter (which was also purchased on Amazon) to confirm the issue.  I made the decision to buy this part from vendor Crank N Charge.  Their staff is knowledgeable and shipped the item right away.Essentially if your Toyota has a good battery and your car goes click, click, click intermittently before it starts, more than likely the solenoid contacts need to be replaced.  I'm mechanically inclined so I took it upon myself to remove the starter from the vehicle, open the unit, disassemble, clean and replace with new components.  Finally the reassembly of the starter and the installation back into the vehicle.  Now my car starts WITHOUT ANY ISSUES WHATSOEVER.  This gives me tremendous peace of mind and saved me countless dollars by just investing some time into a my solid workhorse vehicle.The parts purchased were aftermarket, they are not Denso parts.  The quality seems to be excellent, as the parts consist of two simple copper pieces and a plunger with a copper ring.  Take the time to rebuild the starter correctly to avoid any electrical shorts and this time investment will pay itself off.  I hope this review helps others handle a $300 starter issue with essentially $13 worth of parts.

I heard a lot of good things from a lot of good places about POR-15, and having been on my car about a month, I've got nothing but good things to say about it as well.  I chose to buy the kit over everything separately, simply because I was only buying it for a few small rust spots on my car (early 90's Honda's are rustbuckets. So reliable though!).  I strongly suggest you review what you're going to be painting and get a good idea how much paint you're going to need.  The reason I gave the product 4 stars, is that you really need to finish your coats and do everything you want to do with the paint in one shot.  It dries so fast that it may very well be dry in the can by the next day.  And that's it, it turns completely solid, and has no use but taking up space in a garbage bag.  I don't know if the other POR-15 cans are like this, but again, try to size up what you need so you don't end up wasting a ton.Aside from that, everything is wonderful.  The marine clean and the metal ready work well, some reviews say they're not necessary, I think they very much are.  Especially if you're doing exactly what POR-15's purpose is: painting over rust.  I don't think the paint would have adhered very well if I just tried to brush all the metal flakes and dust off with my bare hand.  The paint is pretty easy to work with too, it's thick and is easy to apply on bumpy rusty steel.  Be very careful with it though!  If you drop it, whatever it splashes is on black forever.  It'll also be on your hands for days if you get any on yourself.  The rubber gloves came for a reason, use them at all times.  Take your time, do a good job.  It will look great, and stop the rust from spreading where you're painted.

I decided to go with a rebuilt AC/Delco over the other products and it cost me the price of a replacement pump PLUS labor I could have done myself.  The item arrived as promised, pulley was pressed on by a pro and installed with a simple three-bolt application.  Took the vehicle in for State safety inspection and the State inspector found fluid leaks on the PS-pump, so I had to pay an additional $70 mechanic fee to replace the rebuilt AC/Delco I just purchased: with another pump from the mechanics provider.  The issue was not the pump mechanism, but the reservoir that was part of the pump purchased.  It appears they may have missed a quality control check on the reservoir which resulted in the one I received leaking at the seams on back of the reservoir.  So for the few bucks I saved, here are the additonal costs:$69.00 new PS pump (but will be refunded by Amazon)$20.00 non-refunded core charge since I have to return this product to Amazon$70.00 mechanic labor charge (not kidding, just to change 3-bolts)$  8.00 2-bottles of power steering fluidSo nearly $100.00 additional out of pocket (and that is if I don't have to replace the $20.00 pulley I just purchased)I will always continue to purchase through Amazon as their customer care and return policy is very customer friendly, but on items like these, do yourself a favor and go for the new if this is any sign of the quality/inspection control for the rebuilts/remanufactured.

I read the negative review from a few years ago, and still thought to myself, they cant be that bad.  I drive a lowered civic, with aftermarket header and exhaust.  I'm use to a rough and loud ride, i figured these mounts cant make that much of a difference, its not like I'm use to driving a Cadillac, Wow was I wrong. After two weeks, i pulled these out today and installed new regular rubber mounts.Good:  these inserts fit perfectly into the stock mounts, even though one of my mounts was completely torn into two pieces. They are easy to install and fit securely into the mounts. They are a good product.Bad: These inserts basically turn your mounts into solid mounts. Every Vibration from the engine transferred directly to the cars body.  This isnt to bad at cruising speed, but was terrible at idle.  At stoplights, my front bumper rattled, the steering wheel shook, Sunroof cover rattled, the change in my center console danced around, etc...  On top of that there was a heavy drone inside the car, from the lack of sound deadening, coupled with the vibration.Opinion:  If you need solid mounts for a high power car/race car, and you dont care about excessive noise, these are perfect for you.  If you need new mounts for the car you drive everyday, spend the money and get new rubber mounts, you will be much happier.

I took a chance and ordered the switch anyway.  It arrived today, and except for color was an exact match of my exisitng switch. On the 5.3 litre GM engines, BEWARE there is an oil filter screen directly below this sensor.  REMOVE IT and throw it away.  It is meant to filter oil before the sensor , but mine plugged and i cleaned it a yr ago with carb cleaner, but plugged again. I removed the screen filter with a pick, and installed the sensor approx 6 months ago--still works fine. Filters havent been around under the sensors for 50 yrs but im sure that its there for a reason.....but i was tired of dealing with it.  Sensor can be installed without removing intake plenum, just use a socket and a u-joint swivel and you can access the sensor- its a 30 min job.....i can do it in 5 min now that i know how to do it. good luck. remove that oil filter screen under the sensor!!

WHere does all that noise come from?  Is it the springs in the clutch?  Is it the valve train?  (sounds like lugging the engine at low RPMs and throttle).  Its a shame that we can't have our cake and eat it too.The flywheel creates a much more responsive engine.  It is quite noticeable.  The only thing I did was replace the clutch and flywheel, and it was a completely different car when I pulled it out of the garage.  Other than the noise, excellent.  It feels a lot stronger.  Revs faster.  Might be a lot of seat of the pants due to removing the buffered dual mass flywheel.  It feels like the engine is attached to the wheels a lot more than it used to.Clutch pedal feels better than stock, but not firm.  Still less firm than my wife's focus ST.Again, other than the noise, it didn't lose any of its drivability.  Just a shame about the noise.  I suppose an excuse to get a loud exhaust.What else can you do when your stock clutch isn't handling your horsepower?  I'm not going to risk going     cheap     and just throwing in a disc, or just doing the clutch and pressure plate and worry about the dual mass flywheel exploding on me.  Do it right, do it once, live with the consequences.

I just finished installing this part.  While it may be as good as original, I can't rate it any better for the following reasons:  As other reviewers noted, it is different from original, there are NO instructions, and it is missing parts (2 nuts as mentioned in other reviews).  Some may be smarter or luckier than me, but I found it to be a royal pain to figure out correct angle/installation.  As for the references to YouTube instructions, from what I found (and I looked) there are no videos that cover the most difficult part of job: how to fit in a part that looks considerably different from the one you just removed.  For those who are where I was 2 hours ago:- Get the 2 nuts (10 mm) before you try to install new part.- Attach the arm (to left) with the protruding bolts through door w/ new nuts.- Once this is in place, it may be easier to figure out how to attach part (it DOES fit).- When in place properly, the motor should sit in upper right corner, pointing straight up,  if you are looking at it straight on (as if you could see through the door panel); if you look down from above, you see the cylinder shape of top of motor).- The four original bolts (in rectangular pattern) will go in place once it is sitting properly.- You will have 3 extra bolts from original that aren't needed .Good luck.

I installed this on my '91 Camaro. It is identical to the original.  Fitment was perfect, it functions properly, and actually raises and lowers the window faster than the original motor ever did.  When the other side burns out I'll be buying the same one.

My '01 Grand Cherokee window regulator went out in the middle of a snow storm! Ug.  So I went to the dealership and the quoted me $350 to replace the regulator!  The part from the dealer is over $200!  Then I found it here on Amazon for $57!!  SOLD!  So I purchased the regulator, and had it replaced and working again in around 45 minutes by doing it myself.  Was an easy replacement.  I would highly recommend this product!I gave 4 stars as there were no instructions, but once you get the door panel off it's easy to see how it goes in (by looking at the one already in there).  Also there are online help guides for Jeep window regulator replacements.  I don't think power window motors were ever very strong for the Jeep.  I have a dealer installed one on the drivers side, and the Amazon/self installed one on the right, and both motors sound weak.  However, since I have experience with the expensive and lesser expensive replacements, I hands down recommend the Amazon replacement.This is a great product that will save you hundreds! :)

I ordered the regulator to replace the one in my 2001 Chevy Silverado passengers door. The part arrived just as promised by Amazon. Opening the box I found the regulator, a piece of paper with information type on it describing the possible changes from the OEM part.  A small plastic bag with two nuts and a bolt in it. I removed the door panel. Taped the window and removed all the bolts. Removed the old regulator. Just as I figured the control cable had rusted and broken. I compared the new one to the OEM. On the bottom of the regulator where there was two bolts, there are welded studs on the new one.. Also, a support bracket mid way on the right side of the part is not present on the new one. It installed with ease. Studs lined up, all bolts lined up with no problems. Window clamps appeared to be the same as the OEM and tightened to the glass. Powered up and a few test runs all appeared to be fine. Time will tell.The paper work explained the difference of the OEM and the replacement with pictures, its a copy, but readable.I hope the missing support on the right side of the frame does not cause any problem later but time will tell. The paper work shows a picture and explains the missing point of contact.If you want to review the removal/installation of the door regulator, there's lots of videos online to show you the proper way to repair your regulator.The up/down speed appeared normal and non-laboredThis is an easy repair for the mechanically challenged.It took about an hour or so. Most of that was taking my time and removing the door panel, plastic and wire's and reinstalling them. Take your time and all will work out for this product.The part was priced anywhere from $40.00 to $60.00 dollars cheaper then I found at Auto Zone or Advanced Auto. These are the two parts places around me.I'll update if any problem with it, but so far so good...I HOPE to get years out of it.
so far so good no problems yet, but only time will tell. Dorman is a popular name as I have bought other products and haven't had any problems?
Customer satisfaction just like i espect it to be my order was on time the part was new the price was fair

This unit saved me a couple hundred bucks which my former mechanic wanted to charge me.  He had supposedly fixed it a year prior and then the window regulator busted again! Wasn't too hard to install.  Thank you Amazon!!!!!!!Long live Amazaon!!!!!!!

I was searching for a good name brand regulator, and i ended up buying this crap.... the brackets didnt even fit my 2003 honda lx complete waste of MY money!! Please dont buy from them !!!Dorman 741-306 Honda Accord Front Driver Side Power Window Regulator with Motor

Great product and service. Product came within days, however I had to wait until after Isaac to put them in. Great product

The original power window mechanism was giving me fits for some time, it worked about half the time but you never knew if it would be raining.  I found a You Tube Video that made it look pretty easy so I being reasonably handy gave it a try.  The video was not as clear in the descriptions as it could have been, I think the guy did it several times before making his video and along the way he left out some of the little things that would have clarified the directions.  These being the things that after the second time must have seemed insignificant to him, but not to me on my first time.I ordered this Dorman part and when it arrived I rounded up a friend to pass tools and hold stuff and to be ready with the bandages.The job was easy once I went over what I was seeing 3 or 4 times, I may have been better off without the video, but it did provide a tool list and some insight.Total time about 1 hr, no damage, no blood....well a little bit, there are a lot of burrs, be careful.The Dorman part works better than the OEM part and now I am going to do the Passenger door, just need that part number now.If you are a 3 or better on a 10 point mechanic scale, go for it.
Fit perfectly in my 2001 chevy suburban 3/4 ton . Installed inless than half an hour start to finish. As ling as it lasts it was well worth it. Saved about 90 dollars from a shop doing it.

The spring snapped so I had to use the original spring that was already in the lock. The lock did nave a broken clip and the clip in this packet was just the fix. It is a great product and recommend this purchase for folks with an inoperable lock.
It fit,and works great,it was easy to install! I would recommend this product to any do it yourselfer,thank you!Cya Tuna Vic
Very easy to install in 2004 Kia Sedona.  Exactly the same as the original.  Amazon had this for about $60 less than any local auto parts store.

Works well so far.  Part looks very similar to the Honda part, except it may have been missing one wire clip that the Honda part had, but it's not really necessary. Both the original regulator in the each front door plus one Honda replacement have broken the same way.  Hopefully Dorman improved on the design, but I won't know for sure for a few years.

Exact fit no complaints I replaced this after troubleshooting my washer lead me to believe that it was the pump. It turned out to be the board but hey ... its got a new pump and board now.

we thought this would be a little bit thicker or sturdier, but still, it is comfortable to sit on and we use it every day when we are outside with our dogs. I think for the price it is worth it. ordered it fast and got it fast! overall, are pleased with it.

I ordered the Mopar Windshield Wiper Spray Nozzles for a Mazda3 and they fit perfectly. The Amazon online vehicle verification confirmed that these would fit my vehicle, which was VERY helpful. These sprayers are exactly what I wanted for my car.
I was happy with the product.  Everything worked well except that I needed one more piece:  a  #34;T #34; or  #34;Y #34; fitting to finish the job.

I used these on a 2009 Ford Focus, but I needed to buy an additional T connector because both nozzles were fed from the same hose and my original was broken. Basically, the hose that comes from the fluid source first hits the passenger side, so you need it to flow up at that point but also continue to the driver's side - hence the need for a T.
Worked just like it was supposed to and expected.

so far they have sent two batteries  and both do not work it says they are for the dc 35 Dyson but the control resistances are different than the original. So it does not work. so one make them wrong or marked them wrong.

Not giving 5 stars as I'm not convinced the vinyl/rubber wrap designed to keep snow and ice off will be very durable, time will tell.

I installed a set of these on my fiancee's '04 Honda Accord (a 26-inch blade on the driver side, an 18-inch blade on the passenger side).  Even after several months the driver-side blade is still too rigid and too curved to work - this results in it doing an excellent job at the ends of the blade but missing a large spot right in the middle.  This results in a large unwiped spot right in the driver's line of sight.
Just installed this product on my Honda S2000.  Installation was easy and has been streak free in both rain and slush spray from snowy roads.
My wife can't stop thanking me for these great wipers. Tried two other major name brands in less than one year and both made too much noise after just 4 months of use.

The days of $20 windshield wiper blades are here. These expensive blades do no better than the Anco standbys that cost 1/4 the price. Replace your Anco's once a year and don't waste your money on hyped, overpriced blades. The Anco's work great and do just as good of a job. If you want even better, but a bottle of Rain-X and apply it a few days before the forecast predicts rain. All of this is still cheaper!

These wiper blades have been great so far. It hasn't rained much out here in California so I'll just have to wait and see. First big storm is due at the end of this week so I'm sure these blades will get a work out.

It worked good at first then it slowly degrades to where it just smears. The 19     works fine for the first two months which lasted longer. Love these wipers. I bought based off of other ratings and now they are the only wipers I purchase. I have bought several.

Like another reviewer I am OCD about the cleanliness of y windshield. I have a 2012 Cadillac SRX and tried this product. The results are not satisfying at all. I bought this after having a normal shaped wiper blade. This wiper blade is more curved and wipes the window completely clear. perfect fit for g35. Thanks!CONS:the wiper makes slight noise when there isn't much water on the window

Perfect replacement for the rear window wiper on my 2011 Chevy Equinox LT. The install could have been easier, but I blame that on Chevy and the design of the rear wiper handle.

I bought a pair of these to replace the disintegrating OEM blades on a 2006 E91 BMW 325xi. Installation wasn't the easiest, as BMW, in its infinite complicating wisdom, uses a special pin mount instead of the usual U-hook. Attachment involved removing a piece from the blade mount, and forcing the slightly-too-small pin hole on the blade onto the slightly-too-large pin on the wiper arm. (There are two pin holes on the wiper mount: a little too small, and way too large.)Note that these blades are reversible on their mounts, to match the curvature of your windshield. The blade carrier separates from the piece that attaches to the wiper arm, and can be reattached facing either left or right. Until I figured this out, the left blade kept a triangle of windshield directly in front of the driver's face un-wiped. I'm guessing that this is probably in the manual, so do read it.As with other Rain-X blades I've installed on other cars, these wipe with the best.
Fantastic alternative to the Audi OEM wiper blades at a fraction of the cost. Very highly recommend!!!Used on:2007 Audi A4 B7
Fit perfectly and was extremely easy to install. It has seen much rain and snow and is still performing well.
It's better than OEM, smoother and quiet, but the last inch or so towards the middle of the car does not wipe flat with the windshield, which means it misses wiping part of the water off.
I have noticed that both blades chatter and streak in light rain. I will not buy these wiper blades again.

Love the Bosch wiper blades. The Evolution series are the best, as they have a cap that swings down and covers the entire insertion area of the wiper. Makes removing the wiper, later on, much easier, because the cap keeps dirt etc. out of the wiper to wiper arm connection area. Unfortunately, these do not fit the rear window of the Subaru Forester 2005, as Amazon's car part finder suggested. The size of the blade is correct, but the connector is wrong.The blade needs to have a large round plastic dowel across the middle of the insertion area, so that the dowel swings up into place on the car's wiper connector arm. The rear window of the 2005 Subaru Forester does not have the standard     push it on the hook of the connector arm     setup. The Advantage series is the same as the Evolution series minus the protection cap, so these should be an excellent blade overall.

Had annoying noise from my brand new set of 20' and 24' wiper blades on my Toyota Camry 2007.  Got a set of Bosch 20-CA and 24-CA to replace the Toyota supplied OEM set.  The 20-CA and 24-CA set works wonderfully quiet with clear visibility in rainy days.  It's yet to find out if it performs well in snowy days!  Additional review on 1/23/2013: works great in snowy days as well!

I really love these blades and bought the winter and 31 series Anco wiper blades because of their high ratings and comparatively lower prices! This product is continually tested as the winter here in my neck of the woods drones on and is performing exceptionally.However, I have found one issue so far that I think would be useful to know about as a first time buyer. These wiper blades are rather un-aerodynamic. Above 55 mph (90 kph) these blades struggle to stay on the surface of my windshield. If it weren't for the     Rain-X     coating that I applied earlier this year, I don't know if I would have any visibility at all at freeway speeds.I have only been using these blades when I know a storm is coming and I'll just be going to work and making short local trips. I switch them out for the standard 31 series blades when I don't need them. I really don't mind it because visibility is something that I worry about more than most others may. I almost enjoy investing quite a bit of time and effort into fending off and conquering winter weather. Using them less and keeping them indoors while I'm not using them also means that these blades may last me a few years. I still do not regret the investment but am glad I also bought the 31 series at the same time.

Being old and not able to reach well anymore, I did not install this myself. However, I did have my friend actually follow the instructions provided with the wiper. He had it installed in a minute or so and it was simple (I have done this in the past).Next, I waited for rain on a day I was going somewhere. We've been in a drought and I wasn't going to rush out in the middle of the few pop-up lightning storms we've had. Finally, all came together and I could test the wiper.Bottom line? It wipes. It wipes well. I'll buy a matching wiper for the passenger side when the current one starts to wear - or give up due to old age if the drought continues.
Bought these for my 92 Miata. Great value and much better than my old ones. Quiet and don't leave any streaks. Hopefully they hold up for a while.

I thought I had installed these improperly because they did not work well and left huge streaks across the window where they didn't touch the glass - but no, they're just incredibly bad wipers.  In the future I will spend a little more for a better product.

Won't be buying this brand again, I will spend the extra cash on the rain-x brand next time!

Just about all wipers are the same.  They start to not work after a few months. these work great on my SUV and they do not skip across the windshield. they give a smooth wipe and i have tried several others.  these consistently perform. and last a year or longer.only thing is they do have a chunky looking connector where they connect onto the wiper arm but on my SUV that looks fine.  may not look as streamlined on a sports car.

I needed a new rear wiper blade for my '04 Ford Escape. Target/Home Depot/Costco type stores don't carry anything outside the range of lengths that fit the front wipers (16 #34;-22 #34;) so I ordered it here. The blade snapped in place with the J hook and works perfectly. No complaints.

It was with GREAT anticipation that I waited for my opportunity to acquire my Valeo Frameless ULTIMATE All-Season  22 #34; Wiper.  The stories of prowess shared by my fore-fathers were legendary.  My mother spoke of Valeo, himself, as the master of all wipers and was clearly the most superior at removing debris from surfaces.In driving through my neighborhood, I saw the drone lifting off from my neighbor's front yard.  Upon closer look, I saw a glow of light from the sky shining down on the box.  It was as though the heavens were shining down on the very cardboard box containing my 22 #34; wiper.  As I reached the front porch, I quickly realized the wiper must be inside.  (Of course, I realized this after I put the box in my car and drove directly home and into my garage, where I ripped open the box with my bare hands.)I have acquired many smiley face boxes in a similar manner, but this one was the box of all boxes.  Upon opening the box, the 22 #34; wiper instantly flew from the opening and began rubbing across my car.  The rust bubbles and mud disappeard, then i noticed the paint shined like new. I have no idea how it worked that magic, but it was as though Frosty the Snowman, himself, was behind it.  I thought 22 #34; wipers were only for glass windsheilds, but this 22 #34; one... this ULTIMATE All-Season Valeo 22 #34; wiper was not only 'All-Season,' but it was also 'All-Car' and 'All Miracle! #34;As it glided across the paint, scratches vanished.  Across the chrome, all pitting removed.  I was astonished to see rubber actually re-appear on the tire tread as it gently stroked across it.  By the time the wiper finished, my car not only looked new again, it was a completely different color.I assure you that if you buy this wiper, and use it on your car, you will be more than thrilled.WARNING:  Use on your wife at your own risk.  After seeing how it made my car look new, I could not help but wonder if it could do the same for my wife.  After using it on my wife, (just a light touch), she was transformed to the beautiful woman I married all those years ago.  Her body was all firm and tight with skin as beautiful and smooth as a baby's skin.  Unfornately, she took one look in the mirror and instantly left me for my neighbor who had ordered the 24 #34; wiper.  I never realized she would leave me just to get a man who had 2 more inches.

While I can't attest to the ease of installation, since Pep Boys installed the pair I presently have on my car - in 2009!!!  I just ordered my first replacement pair after 4 1/2 years.  (OK, so they probably should have been replaced a few months ago, but we didn't have much rain the last 3 months or so.)Even if they had lasted 1 year, I would have been happy, as I usually have to replace wiper blades 1-2X/year.  These wipers were subjected to 3 years in Houston and 1.5 in NJ, and survived 100 degree plus weather, drought (they didn't succumb to dry rot)and, conversely, Houston's notorious rainy weather when the drought finally ended, as well as the blizzard of 2010 that dumped 4' of snow in the Philly area.If this pair lasts as long, they may outlive the car (2002 Saab 9-3). I can't believe I'll get another 4 years out of a pair of wiper blades, but the good solid grip of these on the windshield at all speeds will guarantee clear vision in the worst weather, regardless of how long they last.  That is reason enough for me to continue using Bosch wipers.

These have to be the best wiper blades on the market. Not spectacular, and if they are near the edge of a curved window, they form to the shape after a bit. but when you go to use them, they leave a streak of water where they are bent.

Easy install, I've been through a few car washes since getting a set of these for my '08 Suzuki SX-4 and live in a high wind area but they haven't had any wear show up yet after a month. No complaints about this product, it clearly gets the job done, especially when my windshield is treated with other Rain-X products.
This is an exact fit (no pun intended) replacement for the Subaru Outback rear wiper. I can not vouch for quality of durability, I just installed it, but at least installation was quick and easy.
Hard to find these in our area. These fit our Subaru Forester perfectly. They were shipped promptly after we placed the order.

My car uses the 20A on the passenger side and the 26A on the drivers side.This blade is easy to install, and that's half the battle. Before you order from Amazon, be sure to use the pop-up link to find the proper size for your vehicle. The blades come in both A and B sizes and different lengths. Some vehicles take different lengths for each side of the wind-shield. My Ford Edge takes the 26 A and the 20A.  I did not see a size listed on the website for the rear window wiper.I went to the Bosch web site before installing and they have a wonderful, helpful video about installation. Just search it under     wiper blades     on their site. Lots of helpful information there, for someone who never had to change their old blades. The packaging was simple to open after seeing the video. No need for box cutters or scissors like some over packaged goods.Another helpful hint from the video is to place a towel on the windshield in case the blade snaps out of your hand. (prevent a cracked windshield). You are also told the some vehicles require the blade to be in a vertical position before replacing, so sit in the car and turn on the wiper until it is upright. I know it sounds simple to you mechanical types, but tips like these mean a lot to those of us who were used to Service Stations actually giving service and when the local gas station attendant would check your wipers if asked.This is a good product, works well and is easy to do it yourself.

There's no question that the Clear Advantage Beam Wiper Blade from Bosch delivers superior performance. The best test for how well a blade is working is to drive through a gale-force sleet storm and see how well you can see. The Clear Advantage blades stay put on your windshield and they have enough rigidity to keep working even through the most challenging of conditions. However, that's true of most (but not all) of the     premium     blades I've used over the years. But since the Bosch blades cost $2-$4 more per blade than some other name-brand competitors, I deducted one star for overall value.

First of all, all of the reviewers that gave these a negative review before me are all nuts. I've been using these for around a week or so now, and they are by far the best wiper blades you can buy (if you can really get excited about wiper blades). They are very sturdy, hug the windshield smoothly and evenly, and create a streak-free wipe every time, no matter how hard it rains. I have yet to test these in the winter, but with their frame-less design, I doubt these will under-preform. The only reasons I would believe some people don't like these are because those people are either cheap (These are about double the cost of regular blades, but are definitely worth it) or they don't use the Rain-X Windshield Treatment in addition to these. Like with Rain-X Washer Fluid, even though it doesn't mention this on the bottle, if you don't use the Rain-X Treatment along with it, it will make your windshield even dirtier after using it. It wasn't until I used the Rain-X Treatment along with the Washer Fluid until the product worked like a charm. The Rain-X Windshield Treatment does an awesome job at increasing visibility during showers, so it's a good thing to use anyways. this is the exact piece we were looking for.My wife's 2007 RAV4 had this wiper wore down for some time, and we could not get it from anywhere. Finally she found it and had me to get this for her. Shipping was fast, and was the exact replacement piece.Highly recommended.

I'm comparing this to a     premium     Michelin wiper blade I had installed previously on my Civic, which I had purchased at the local Wal*Mart, and I think it holds up quite nicely. First of all, they both have a bracketless construction which prevents chunks of ice from getting stuck between the arms which would otherwise cause the wiper to become ineffective. Come blizzard time here in New England, that will be much appreciated.  This wiper installed more easily than the Michelin; the default mounting bracket worked perfectly and there was only one way--the correct way--to snap the blade onto my wiper arm. In addition, the mounting bracket is somewhat closed to the elements, and should prevent ice and other foreign objects from getting lodged there.So, I would characterize this wiper as well and thoughtfully constructed.[Update: wiper failed when the blade shredded after 2,5 years of service, pretty good as these things go.]As for the breast cancer awareness ribbon logo, it is clearly visible to the driver. I don't know what to think about that. My dear sister is a breast cancer survivor, and the disease has cost me in emotional pain; maybe I don't want to be reminded of that pain every day on the way to work.

Have to wait for rain, but as best I can tell a good oem replacement refill for the 2009 Mazda 6, s model, 6 Cly. This is the second generation Mazda 6, and I believe model changed again in 2014.Finding the right refill can be a challenge. Local pep boys does not stock refills and wants you to get complete wiper arm, Napa had generic refill but they lacked the metal strips. The metal strips are what gives the blade its spring, which in turns allows its to form fit to the glass.I measured my old ones, and they were 8mm. Just like these. As there are wide, narrow, extra narrow, best to measure first.For what it's worth, parts search returned these,     45-240 and 46-180     for driver/passenger respectively, they also listed the trico     17-240 and 17-180    . Not sure what those would have done and not clear what the difference is.Install tip: follow directions. ;)Seriously, they are picture based directions that have 3 steps so not hard. The metal strips can fall out easily. The new refill should have plastic clips that keeps everything together. Leave the clips on, and as you insert the new refill they will be pushed to the end and come off.

I bought 2 pairs of these for use with a Ford and a Mazda. Both have narrow wipers of appropriate length and are supposed to be compatible with this product.The refills are just a tiny bit too wide (not more than 0.5mm or 1mm too wide) and that makes them 100% unusable. On the Ford, where I was lucky and I managed to squeeze the refills in it took FOREVER to get it right (I spent almost 30 minutes on the first wiper and about 15 on the second)On the Mazda, I just couldn't get it done. I had to use pliers to slightly widen the gap on the little metal pieces that are supposed to hold the refill just to get it through and ended up destroying my blades.I cannot think of a single good thing to say about this item!do yourself a favor and buy a different product.
